##16,000 telephone helplines

Micro Signal Zhenshigushi1

Function description, every day a moving original true story.

Medical supplies for the new pneumonia outbreak are running low, and calls for help are being sent out everywhere. At the same time, overseas Chinese moved to purchase scarce supplies in foreign countries, but suffered from lack of channels to reach the domestic front against the epidemic. A green corridor has emerged, setting up a trans-oceanic lifeline for relief supplies.

Year: 2020

Location: overseas, Hubei

Year: 2020

Location: overseas, Hubei

A freight train bound for Wuhan

At a little after 10 a.m. on January 27, Shi Ling drove a white van, the Shanghai BCW936, to the exit of the Hankou Highway. It was the second day of his trek from Shanghai to Wuhan with a shipment of donated medical supplies from overseas. Seeing the lights in Hankou, he knew he had only a few miles to go.

Shi Ling works in a Baishi Logistics Office in Pudong, Shanghai, and is usually in charge of the distribution line. On the night of January 25, he saw a message in the work group, the network needs to transport a batch of supplies to Wuhan, recruiting a volunteer driver, he signed up. His wife could not stay, tears of pain, request to follow the car was also rejected by stone.

The next day, shilling drove the van alone. The cargo, which included 480 N95 masks, 1,560 pairs of goggles and 1,122 sets of protective clothing, was donated overseas by the New York Area Alumni Association of Wuhan University and the Chinese American Association of Social Workers. They were packed in large corrugated boxes, sealed by customs and placed in 8-ton pick-up trucks that loosely covered half the cargo.

Shi Ling puzzled why did not fill the car, the boss told him: Epidemic Emergency. He was the last link in the green passage line for the newbie rescue, and there were plenty of supplies to follow, as well as the use of the route.

Shilling and his white van

Shi Ling carried with him several documents that listed the medical supplies, the vehicle he was driving and the identity of the driver. On the way to meet the road check, he took out a few documents and identity cards, check and release.

Getting off the highway from Hankou, the truck Hu BCW936 pulls into the last checkpoint before Wuhan City. The inspection and Quarantine staff at the intersection motioned stone order to open the box, want to check whether the inside for medical supplies re-release.

Stone Ling did not dare to directly promise, seal is in Shanghai when the customs paste, he was afraid of demolition, to Wuhan Grantee questioned he secretly break seal steal goods.

Under the Stuck in the Middle, he obtained permission, filmed the process, sent it to the company's Workgroup, and issued a certificate of communication to the Green Channel volunteers.

Not yet into Wuhan, Shi Ling has felt the surrounding medical supplies shortage. Workers in Wuhan wear face masks and protective clothing. Only when they speak can they tell the difference between men and women. When reloaded, they awkwardly check and sign.

By contrast, wearing an N95 mask, casual clothes and a jacket, Shi felt his shields were thin, like short-sleeved shorts on a winter day, and suddenly he was nervous.

When the staff finished checking the container to help him close the door, Shi Ling found a place to wash his hands, before entering Wuhan changed a clean N95 mask, continue to Wuhan.

Donors

In fact, on January 25, the day before Shi Ling officially went on a mission, the "green passage of rookie relief supplies" was just completed.

In the last week of January, the news began reporting a shortage of medical supplies in Hubei Province, as more and more designated hospitals on social media asked for masks, protective clothing and goggles.

After hearing the news, people abroad began to act in the hope of being able to send relief supplies to the country. Concerned about the difficulty of transporting the materials, Ali Cainiao took the initiative to establish a "green passage" .

Unlike the driver shiling, the Rookie Customer Service Volunteer ruoyu is the first link in the corridor. After the hotline service collects and records the donor's request, she will be in charge of the first return visit.

A chinese-american man who has been running a gas station in Canada for years has dug through his stash of Hazmat suits. He then called his supplier, promised to double the price, bought goods that the supplier had not had time to sell to other customers, and eventually cobbled together 516 protective suits to send back home to the medical staff fighting the epidemic.

In the snow of foreign countries, until the night before the logistics, the men also continue to shop around for protective clothing.

A Chinese tour guide in Dubai has asked a group of returning tourists to donate batches of self-collected masks to the front line of the epidemic by carrying hand luggage to the country before calling the hotline of Ruoyu.

And as international tour groups shut down and Dubai's flights to China ground to a halt, the guide found Ruoyu and tried to get supplies to China through the Green Passage: "these are my last efforts. "

Ms. Zhang, who returned from Italy to visit relatives during the Spring Festival, called the hotline. She was unable to return to work in Italy because of the blockade, but this was not her call to call a hotline -- she reached out to mask manufacturers in Italy to find out how to deliver the masks to medical staff at designated hospitals.

She hopes to find a long-term turnover, storage channels, to Wuhan on the hands of the first-line medical staff.

In the face of each donor, if jade first to confirm with each other, whether to meet the use of green channel conditions, inform each other need to prepare documents, and help connect in charge of customs and international logistics volunteers.

At its peak, she visits nearly 40 donors a day. Ruoyu's child is just one year old, and every night at 9:00 pm, she tucks her child into bed and begins the work by phone or Wechat, sometimes not resting until the wee hours of the morning.

Photo: ruoyu holding her sleeping child at work

Working with people through words and sounds, ruoyu has encountered a variety of personality donors.

That Ms. Zhang is a practical person. When told that the individual can not be the main donor, Ms. Zhang immediately asked Ruoyu: whether can use the name of mask manufacturers, or other social organizations to donate.

Ruoyu reminded her that her name would not appear on the donor list in the future. Ms. Zhang thanked if jade remind her, and comfort if jade this does not matter, as long as the material can be used by the medical staff other all does not matter.

A middle-aged businessman told ruoyu that he had bought a batch of medical supplies in Indonesia and wanted to connect the green channel and donate them to a hospital in Zhejiang Province. Ruoyu guessed that this was an eager and efficient man who had confirmed with the hospital that the supplies would be accepted before purchasing them, saving the volunteers some time in communicating with the recipients.

If the jade remembers, his speech speed is particularly quick, lets the human want to carry out his order immediately. When Ruoyu told him that he might not be able to make the donation through the green channel because of conditions at his foreign company, the voice on the phone went higher: "help, they really don't have any supplies, you can't watch them like this. "

Fortunately, later problems one by one, Hangzhou businessmen arrived in domestic transshipment of goods.

In early February, Ruoyu saw on the Internet the Hunan Red Cross Society's acceptance of public donations. On the list, enterprises often donate hundreds of thousands of money and materials, and with these enterprises, individual donations of materials may be only a few hundred sets, a few dollars. They're silent donors.

But, like the people who answered her phone, she said, they had no access to the stores where they could get supplies, and sometimes paid several times as much as they used to.

To create a life-form

Customer Service "Ruoyu" is only the beginning of this transport line. Global concerns are pouring into China, where Ruoyu and her colleagues are facing huge, scattered and urgent transportation needs. And the coordinator of this special international transport route, is a woman named "crazy mo" in the workplace.

On the first day of the Lunar New Year, at 1:00 p.m. , crazy Mo, who was watching the drama on the SOFA, received a phone call from his boss. Ali cainiao decided to cooperate with domestic and overseas logistics partners to open a global green channel for free transportation of relief supplies in Hubei.

The preparation of such a cross-border transport route is a strange attempt for everyone.

At that time, there were two ways to send goods purchased overseas to Wuhan: Sending special people to bring them home to donate, or entering the country through special tax-free channels.

However, the tax-free channel only accepts donations destined for state-level charities, and ordinary people are not familiar with the process, nor can they contact domestic charities. As a result, many aid-hubei materials are trapped in the purchase, which is to open the green channel to face the first hurdle.

On the afternoon of the first day, crazy Mo and his colleagues urgently contacted the various leaders to negotiate a solution: Their team was responsible for contacting five charities in the country and handling the formalities for the donation. And to help charities distribute goods more quickly, CAINIAO will be in charge of the distribution of all goods in the country.

To Save Time, the rookie team decided to forgo shipping, but international airfreight costs were high, and Ali volunteered to cover some of the costs. So a passage of life, from all over the world to home, was built. The United States, Indonesia, Croatia, Poland, and far-flung countries on the map are sending out donations in record numbers.

Work began, crazy mo only know, holding materials in the overseas anxiously waiting for people in what state. Wenzhou Overseas Chinese in Europe to purchase 1.52 million masks, protective clothing and other medical supplies, but encountered large-scale grounding flights, desperate. When I got through to the hotline, it was like rain.

"I got a mask here! " Posted an online link to a donation group of Chinese students. Others quickly bought out the masks on the link.

One student, who knew that crazy horse was a rookie employee, shouted, "quick, quick, Ali's men are in the crowd. If there's anything you need, speak quickly. " It was the first time crazy horse hosted foreign students, unlike the steady work of businesses and institutions, the students have endless excited mood, crazy mo feel childishness lovely, and moved by their cavity warm blood.

With more donors and a temporary team of six running low, crazy horse began pulling in colleagues. They laugh at themselves like "pyramid scheme" , crazy to their "off line" , the work group in two days to expand to more than 70 people.

After the call, the customer service team registers the basic information of the donor, screens out the list of eligible donors, and informs the donor of the necessary procedures and follow-up procedures. At the same time, the transport team co-ordinate the landing route of the goods to ensure that the first time after the procedures to bring the goods back to the country.

Colleagues formed a fine network, quickly convey the needs of donors, firmly hold all the material will flow to Hubei.

One afternoon, a Chinese American donor sent a message from the group, saying that he did not have a large quantity of goods and wondered if he could help carry them. The local colleague in charge of the docking immediately replied: "Please trust us. " Crazy Mo calculated the time difference, that time should be 1:30 a.m. in the United States.

A shipment of supplies from Japan enters the greenway

During the 10-day vacation at home, except for sleep time, crazy moshou in front of the computer almost did not move. Parents see crazy mo so, put food and water on her hand, did not dare to disturb.

And the staff responsible for loading cargo onto planes from foreign destinations are constantly sending out bad news.

Affected by the epidemic, overseas flights to China are being canceled, access to the channel is getting fewer and fewer. As of Feb. 4,46 airlines around the world had suspended flights to mainland China, cancelling more than 8,000 flights. As a result, some volunteers experienced three flight cancellations a day and 10 donations were suddenly grounded.

Emperor Xiaowu of Liu Song, the head of international transport, took over the first batch of supplies, which foreshadowed the ups and downs of his volunteer work. The masks, 30,000 in total, were donated from Mexico to the cities of Wuhan and Wenzhou, sponsored by the Overseas Chinese living in Wenzhou, Mexico.

The masks were supposed to land in Shanghai Pudong International Airport, but a few days before take off, policy was being tightened and customs officials assessed that the shipment would be difficult to land in Shanghai as originally planned.

After years of doing business overseas with Ali, Emperor Xiaowu of Liu Song was familiar with customs policy. After several communications adjustments, he decided to ship the goods to Hong Kong, land to Guangzhou, and then from Guangzhou to the recipient destination.

Photo by Emperor Xiaowu of Liu Song late at night in the face mask logistics

After that, every time there was a supply flight ready to take off. Emperor Xiaowu of Liu Song is always ready to come up with a backup plan. The computer screen at his home in Hangzhou was crowded with flight charts from all over the world, and he could not breathe a sigh of relief until the planes carrying supplies were off the ground.

And deliver it to them

As soon as the plane touched down, Li Jun, the man in charge of domestic transportation, had to respond quickly.

At Special Times, he and his colleagues try to find areas where they can collect, transport, and deliver goods, and mark out areas that are short of capacity.

To a small batch of goods or carpooling, with 9.6 meters of trucks or 7.4 meters of trucks, from which highway intersection, the team will follow up to understand. Until the goods successfully delivered, received a letter of acceptance to the hospital, it is considered to complete a long relay.

In addition, Li Jun's team is responsible for transporting relief supplies across the country. On Jan. 26, when the Wuhan Union Hospital ran out of supplies, 40 units from nine provinces were ready for delivery.

Most of the goods came from remote areas such as Heilongjiang, Inner Mongolia, Hainan and Gansu, and some were scattered among different units in the same province. During the Spring Festival holiday, logistics resources are scarce, the unit can not solve the transport problem, so found the rookie.

Li Jun received the notice, the first time to find the rookie logistics partners, he was worried about the transport capacity, difficult to take care of, did not expect all partners to say nothing, have joined the transport team, overnight and Li Jun developed a transport plan.

Supplies from Heilongjiang, Jiamusi and Fujin take so long to travel by road that they have to be flown to Wuchang and then taken by train to Wuhan. Given the different capabilities of individual couriers, each item requires Li Jun's team to evaluate resources and capacity to see which one is best suited to the task.

The next day, each express delivery to the hospitals around the home to collect. Five days later, all aid from the nine provinces was delivered to doctors at the Wuhan Union Hospital.

As of February 13, the GREENWAY has received more than 16,000 donor hotlines. Some 26 million pieces of medical supplies donated by governments, institutions and overseas Chinese organizations from 29 countries and regions have been transported to Wuhan and other places through the green passage for beginners.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A shipment of goods arrived via China Eastern

Wang Long, who is part of a new cross-border logistics team, signed up as a volunteer after being quarantined at home in Huanggang, the province's second-most-affected region, during the Spring Festival. He admits that at times of crisis, public access to information can be overwhelming in remote areas. He had once fished out these faint cries from small towns.

On February 5th, 40,000 masks arrived from France. At first, donors wanted to donate the supplies to a hospital in downtown Wuhan, but the hospital said there were relatively enough surgical masks.

Wang immediately contacted a donor in France and suggested sending the masks to a local hospital near Wuhan, where supplies were scarce and no one was looking. He was trusted to recommend him.

Wang recommends three places: Jingzhou, Xiaogan and Wuxue in Huanggang. On the second day of the Lunar New Year, Wang, a native of Huanggang, saw a call for help from a designated hospital in Wuxue among his friends. He learned that in the hospital, medical staff had no protective masks and wore raincoats as protective clothing, and surgical masks were only enough for 1-2 days.

In the end, donors in France decided to transfer the 40,000 masks to Wuxue Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine.

The masks have found someone who needs them

Along the way, Shi Ling's vigilance over the epidemic gradually accumulated.

Stopping at a gas station in Huanggang, a woman saw the yellow lettering "Wuhan Medical Supplies" on his crate and asked Shi to sell her some face masks. Shi Ling explained to her that medical supplies could not be sold privately. The woman was crying and said, "it's really gone. You can't buy it anywhere. " The woman wore a thin mask, and Shi Lingshan also felt the woman's anxiety.

He walked back to the cab, where his boss gave him five N95 masks before he left, one for the trip, one for the woman, and three for himself. Vague feeling, not yet to Wuhan, so short of supplies?

It was just after 11 a.m. when we entered downtown Wuhan. Shi Ling opened an electronic map and searched for navigation to the donated site. He felt that the length of time in Wuhan was "out of whack" .

His plan was simple: Walk to the location of the donated unit and return immediately to Shanghai. Unexpectedly, after entering Wuhan, due to the restrictions on the passage of goods vehicles and the ban on traffic in the urban area of Wuhan since late January, it took nearly eight hours to detour less than 14 kilometers of roads in the normal urban area on the electronic map.

He hadn't eaten all night and couldn't find a restaurant when he entered Wuhan. Hungry, he felt he couldn't drive for nearly eight hours.

Fortunately, Shi Ling found a traffic police on the roadside to ask for directions. The traffic police saw that his car had a pass and told him that it would not take so long to go directly to the third ring road in the downtown area.

At 5 pm on January 27, Shi Ling finally unloaded the last box of medical supplies after running to two donor sites. Sitting in the truck's cockpit overlooking the park's protective suits, he fired up the van and set off on his way back.

A Green Channel volunteer reminds us that drivers like shilling are "expendable" on the delivery chain. After each trip to Wuhan, they were greeted by a 14-day quarantine at home. In the meantime, they can not return to work, also can not deliver goods to Wuhan again.

Workers hand over supplies

A trip to Wuhan, says Shi, is more tiring than the physical stress. He went to two donor sites and, with the exception of drivers who had come from other parts of the country, the locals wore thick isolation suits, which led him, for some reason, to imagine a virus in the air.

He did not dare to breathe heavily, did not dare to make an expression, for fear of the face and the gap in the mask, the virus ran into the mouth. He was afraid to get sick, afraid to pass the disease to his wife, so on the way, he made a phone call to his wife, his wife to buy good disinfectant and mask.

The first thing he planned to do when he got home was to take off his coat, dispose of any belongings he could throw away in a garbage bag, dispose of any items he couldn't throw away with disinfectant, and wash them thoroughly.

After leaving Wuhan, Shi Ling drove without stopping to a highway service station near Huanggang. He was so sleepy that he slept on the steering wheel for an hour and a half. It was the longest and deepest sleep he had had in two days.

At the beginning of February, the countdown to home quarantine gradually returned to zero, Shi Ling's tension gradually dissipated. Later, several times in the work group to recruit volunteer drivers to Wuhan, Shi Ling also signed up. He still recalls the eerie sight of the empty streets of Wuhan, home to more than 14m people, and fears of disease.

But he also asked himself: If one day I am sick, will someone do this for me?

In the first week of February, 40,000 masks donated from France arrived in Wuhan. Wang has seen the 40,000 masks he handled in the photos, measuring 2.5 cubic meters in size and looking small in the cargo compartment.

When I was preparing to transport it to the temple, I encountered another problem. Due to the traffic control, ordinary cars can not drive from Wuhan to Huanggang. Eventually, after Wang's efforts, they hitchhiked to Wuxue with a local logistics company and ended up at the end of the transport chain.

In Downtown Wuxue, where motor vehicles are restricted from the roads, Wang called the Medical Equipment Department of the Wu Xue Hospital and told them it would take a day and a half to arrange to apply for documents for the vehicles. The female doctor who answered the phone asked Wang Long to tell the address of the logistics network, and the ambulance sent by the hospital took back the 40,000 masks on the same day.

But this is not the end of the drift of these masks.

Wang long asked the doctor, 40,000 masks hospital how long. Wu Point Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine reply, after keeping 10,000 masks, they also put the remaining surgical masks shipped to the surrounding material shortage of small hospitals.

The equipment doctor reported the names of the hospitals receiving supplies to Wang Long, most of which he had never heard of. It is these unknown hospitals, in this epidemic, assume the first-line treatment of small towns.

With the help of Wang long and the hospitals seeking supplies, the supplies from Europe to China have come to the aid of people who would otherwise have been hard to keep track of.
